  "body": "### Component\n\nForge\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [X] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\nforge 0.1.0 (31e4a9d 2022-02-16T00:23:05.596898430+00:00)\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\nforge test\n\n### Operating System\n\nLinux\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nI have found two issues related to Forges `expectEmit`.\r\n\r\nIf compared events have the same name and signature but differ in the number of indexed parameters and at least one such indexed parameter is selected for comparison then Rust panics.\r\n```\r\ncontract Emitter {\r\n    event MyEvent(uint256 indexed param1);\r\n\r\n    function e(uint256 x) public {\r\n        emit MyEvent(x);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\ncontract TestPanicEmits is DSTest {\r\n    event MyEvent(uint256 param1);\r\n\r\n    CheatCodes cheats = CheatCodes(HEVM_ADDRESS);\r\n\r\n    function testPanic() public {\r\n        Emitter emitter = new Emitter();\r\n        cheats.expectEmit(true, false, false, false);\r\n        emit MyEvent(1);\r\n        emitter.e(1);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe second issue pops up when we use low-level calls. In this case, the test for emitted events seems to pass no matter what.\r\n```\r\ncontract Emitter {\r\n    function f() public {\r\n        // this call can be successful or even not\r\n        (bool success, ) = address(this).call(abi.encodeWithSignature(\"g()\"));\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    function g() public {}\r\n}\r\n\r\ncontract TestCallEmits is DSTest {\r\n    event MyEvent();\r\n\r\n    CheatCodes cheats = CheatCodes(HEVM_ADDRESS);\r\n\r\n    function testCallPassing() public {\r\n        Emitter emitter = new Emitter();\r\n\r\n        // we state that we are expecting MyEvent event\r\n        // the four values of expectEmit don't matter in this example\r\n        cheats.expectEmit(true, true, true, true);\r\n        emit MyEvent();\r\n        \r\n        // this will not emit any event so the test should fail, but it passes\r\n        emitter.f();\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n \r\n```",
